{{Infobox Cheese | name = Korbáčik/Korbáčiky | image = [[File:Údený korbáčik (Slovakia).jpg|260px|Korbáčiky]] | othernames = | country = [[Slovakia]] | region = [[Orava (region)|Orava]] | town = | source = Primarily [[Cow]]s / [[Sheep]] | pasteurised = Yes | Made backwards | texture = Medium-hard | fat = | protein = | dimensions = | weight = | aging = 4 weeks - 10 months | certification = No }}
'''Korbáčik''' (IPA: [korbaːt͡ʃik]) is a type of semi-hard or medium hard [[string cheese]]. It originates from the [[Orava (region)|Orava]] region of northern [[Slovakia]]. It is made from [[Smoking (cooking)|smoked]] cheese interwoven into fine braids. The name roughly translates to "little [[whip]]" which refers to the pattern woven onto the strings.
== Content == There are two main variants of the Korbáčik, the smoked and the un-smoked.<ref>{{cite web|title=Korbáčiky|url=http://paulinescookbook.wordpress.com/2011/07/30/korbaciky/|publisher=Paulines cookbook|accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> In addition to these, it is not uncommon to produce salty variants, as well as with [[garlic]]. The basis for the production is milk, either from cow or from sheep.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cerven|first=Jozef|title=Ako sa robia Oravske Korbaciky|url=http://cerven.blog.sme.sk/c/66246/Ako-sa-robia-oravske-korbaciky.html|publisher=sme.sk|accessdate=7 August 2013|language=Slovak}}</ref>
