[[Antarctica]] sits on every [[Meridian (geography)|line of longitude]], due to the [[South Pole]] being situated near the middle of the continent. Theoretically Antarctica would be located in all time zones; however, areas south of the [[Antarctic Circle]] experience extreme day-night cycles near the times of the June and December [[solstice]]s, making it difficult to determine which time zone would be appropriate. For practical purposes time zones are usually based on [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|territorial claims]]; however, many stations use the time of the country they are owned by or the time zone of their supply base (e.g. [[McMurdo Station]] and [[Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station]] use [[Time in New Zealand|New Zealand time]] due to their main supply base being [[Christchurch]], New Zealand).<ref name=DST>{{cite web|url=http://www.timegenie.com/country.time/aq |title=Local Time → Antarctica @ Time Genie |publisher=Timegenie.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-24}}</ref> Nearby stations can have different time zones, due to their belonging to different countries. Many areas have no time zone since nothing is decided and there are not even any temporary settlements that have any clocks. They are simply labeled with [[UTC|UTC time]].<ref name=NZTime>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/city.html?n=468 |title=Current local time in Antarctica – South Pole |publisher=Timeanddate.com |date=2013-04-07 |accessdate=2013-07-24}}</ref>

